	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Danville&#44; Pa</placeName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>January 6&#47;63</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Phila</placeName></p>
				<p>Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It affords me a great Deal<lb/> of pleasure of having opportunity<lb/> again to write a few lines<lb/> to you for which I hope you<lb/> will excuse me.  Above all I have<lb/> the pleasure to announce to<lb/> you that I am <sic>determint</sic><lb/> to <sic>quite</sic> Hazanship <add>&#63;</add> <date>April 1&#47;63</date><lb/> and <sic>summonce</sic> something else<lb/> for the support of my beloved<lb/> family.  I have faithfully<lb/> discharged my Duties for seven<lb/> years &#38; three months&#44; have<lb/> spent all my time for the<lb/> welfare of the Congregation&#44;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)">But I feel myself bound<lb/> now to quit&#44; not because<lb/> I do not love my religion<lb/> any more or feel to be<lb/> ashamed to be a Hebrew minister<lb/> but because I do not and<lb/> never will bow down<lb/> for the Almighty Dollar<lb/> who lives and <add>&#63;</add> all<lb/> Jewish Hearts.  I feel assured<lb/> that I can make my living<lb/> in any other business and<lb/> more honorably than to be the<lb/> minister of a Congregation<lb/> who is governed only by two<lb/> or three who violate the laws<lb/> <sic>dayly</sic> who on <date>Yom Kipur</date><lb/> had their meatshop open<lb/> and the wagon of one came<lb/> before the Synagogue Door<lb/> for Orders.  Dear Sir&#33;<lb/>  I know the most do not<lb/> like to see me leave&#59; but</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>it can not be helped.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In the spring when I come<lb/> to <placeName>Phila</placeName> I will settle my<lb/> account with you.  Do not<lb/> be afraid I am still a faith<lb/>ful servant of the Lord.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">For curiosity I will remark<lb/> to you that last week&#44; <placeName>Danville</placeName><lb/> was honored by a new Jewish<lb/> Rabbi&#44; so he signed his name.<lb/>  The <persName>Rev Dr M. Delbanco</persName>&#44;<lb/> Jewish Rabbi of <placeName>Wilkes Barre</placeName><lb/> preached a sermon last <date>Saturday</date><lb/> and received about &#36;20.00 for it.<lb/>  It was a strange thing to me<lb/> to see a Radical Reformer<lb/> on <date>Friday</date> evening&#44; where he acted<lb/> as Chasan here&#44; singing Le cha Dodi<add>&#63;</add><lb/> and recite Bameh Madlikin<add>&#63;</add>.<lb/>  Who is this <persName>Dr M. Delbanco</persName><lb/> the Jewish Rabbi of<lb/> <placeName>Wilkes <sic>Barri</sic></placeName>&#44; I can<lb/> not remember such a Rabbi</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Be assured dear Sir<lb/> that I will still continue<lb/> to do anything for our holy<lb/> cause.</p>
				<p>Without further statements</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I remain your<lb/> servant</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName role="author">J. Oppenheim</persName></p>
		</body>
